\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
This paper presents GridTokenX, a decentralized peer-to-peer (P2P) energy trading platform built on Solana using the Anchor framework. The system comprises six specialized smart contract programs---Trading, Energy Token, Oracle, Registry, Governance, and Blockbench---implementing a dual-tracker architecture that cryptographically isolates physical energy flow from financial token flow. We detail the design patterns, Cross-Program Invocation (CPI) flows, security mechanisms, and formal verification strategies employed. Empirical evaluation demonstrates sustained throughput of 4,200 TPS with 99.7\% success rate under load, average transaction latency of 420ms, and a 45.5\% compute unit reduction through systematic optimization. A comprehensive test suite of 489 tests achieves 94.2\% code coverage across all programs. Comparative analysis against existing platforms (Power Ledger, Energy Web, WePower) shows 10--100$\times$ throughput improvement and 4--200$\times$ cost reduction. All programs are implemented in Rust using Anchor 0.32.0 with SPL Token-2022 integration, featuring Program Derived Address (PDA) authorities and zero-copy state management. This work contributes a reference implementation for blockchain-based DePIN (Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Network) applications, accompanied by formal security analysis addressing eight attack vectors and STRIDE threat modeling.
\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
Anchor Framework, Solana, Smart Contracts, Energy Trading, P2P Markets, Rust, Blockchain, DePIN
\end{IEEEkeywords}

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}

The global transition to distributed renewable energy generation has created a fundamental mismatch between traditional centralized grid infrastructure and the bidirectional flow of energy in prosumer-rich networks \cite{mengelkamp2018, tushar2020}. In conventional energy markets, consumers passively receive electricity from large-scale generators through a hierarchical distribution network. However, the rapid adoption of rooftop solar photovoltaic (PV) systems, battery storage, and smart meters has transformed passive consumers into active \textit{prosumers}---participants who both produce and consume energy \cite{parag2016, zhou2020}.

Peer-to-peer (P2P) energy trading represents a paradigm shift in which prosumers trade surplus generation directly with neighbors, bypassing centralized intermediaries \cite{sousa2019, zhang2018}. Blockchain technology provides the trust, transparency, and automation required for such decentralized markets through immutable ledgers and programmable smart contracts \cite{andoni2019}. While Ethereum-based implementations dominate the literature, they suffer from high gas costs (\$1--50 per transaction), low throughput ($\sim$15 TPS), and probabilistic finality that limits real-time energy settlement \cite{digiesi2023}.

\subsection{Problem Statement}

Existing blockchain energy trading platforms face three critical challenges: (1) \textit{scalability}---Ethereum-based systems cannot support high-frequency meter readings from thousands of smart meters; (2) \textit{cost}---gas fees make micro-transactions for small energy trades economically infeasible; and (3) \textit{integration}---bridging physical energy metering infrastructure with on-chain state requires robust oracle mechanisms with Byzantine fault tolerance.

\subsection{Contributions}

This paper makes the following contributions:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item A \textbf{modular six-program architecture} on Solana/Anchor that achieves 4,200 sustained TPS with sub-second finality, enabling real-time energy settlement;
    \item A \textbf{dual-tracker protocol} that cryptographically isolates physical energy flow from financial token flow, preventing double-spending through high-water mark enforcement;
    \item A \textbf{comprehensive security framework} addressing eight attack vectors with formal STRIDE analysis and 91 dedicated security tests;
    \item An \textbf{elastic dual-token model} (GRX + CRB) with energy-backed minting that maintains 1:1 kWh parity through oracle-validated meter readings;
    \item A \textbf{production-grade reference implementation} with 489 tests, 94.2\% code coverage, and 45.5\% compute unit optimization through systematic techniques.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{System Overview}

GridTokenX implements a complete vertical stack for P2P energy trading. The \textit{Smart Meter Simulator} provides a Python-based Advanced Metering Infrastructure (AMI) generating cryptographically signed meter readings using Ed25519 signatures. The \textit{API Gateway}, built with Rust/Axum, bridges external systems to the blockchain through authenticated RPC channels. Six specialized \textit{Anchor Programs} on Solana manage core business logic, from user registration through energy settlement. Finally, React-based \textit{web and mobile clients} provide end-user interfaces for trading and monitoring.

\subsection{Anchor Framework}

The system is built on Anchor 0.32.0 \cite{anchor}, a Rust framework for Solana smart contract development. Anchor provides Interface Definition Language (IDL) generation for TypeScript/JavaScript client bindings, CPI abstraction for simplified Cross-Program Invocation, declarative account validation through procedural macros, structured on-chain event emission, and a TypeScript integration testing framework. These capabilities enable rapid development of type-safe, composable programs while maintaining the performance characteristics of native Solana \cite{solana}.

\subsection{Paper Organization}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section~\ref{sec:related} surveys related work in blockchain-based energy trading. Section~\ref{sec:architecture} details the system architecture and dual-tracker protocol. Sections~\ref{sec:programs}--\ref{sec:governance} describe each Anchor program. Section~\ref{sec:security} presents the security analysis. Sections~\ref{sec:tokens}--\ref{sec:processes} cover token economics and process flows. Section~\ref{sec:testing} through Section~\ref{sec:load-tests} present testing and benchmarks. Section~\ref{sec:comparative} provides comparative analysis. Section~\ref{sec:limitations} discusses limitations and future work. Section~\ref{sec:conclusion} concludes.

\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

\subsection{Blockchain-Based Energy Trading}

The intersection of blockchain technology and energy markets has attracted significant research attention. Mengelkamp et al. \cite{mengelkamp2018} proposed one of the earliest P2P energy trading frameworks using Ethereum smart contracts, demonstrating the feasibility of decentralized energy markets in the Brooklyn Microgrid project. However, their implementation suffered from Ethereum's high transaction costs and low throughput, limiting practical scalability.

Tushar et al. \cite{tushar2020} provided a comprehensive survey of P2P energy trading frameworks, identifying key challenges including market design, pricing mechanisms, and regulatory compliance. Their taxonomy categorizes trading platforms by centralization degree, market structure, and settlement mechanism---dimensions that inform our architectural decisions.

\subsection{Commercial Platforms}

Several commercial platforms have emerged in this space. \textit{Power Ledger} \cite{powerledger} operates a hybrid on-chain/off-chain architecture with a custom blockchain achieving approximately 100 TPS at \$0.001 per transaction. While commercially deployed in Australia, Japan, and the US, its proprietary chain limits interoperability and developer ecosystem access.

\textit{Energy Web} \cite{energyweb} targets enterprise utility digitalization using a custom EVM-compatible chain with Proof-of-Authority consensus, achieving approximately 30 TPS. Its focus on large-scale utility partnerships differs from our prosumer-centric approach.

\textit{WePower} \cite{wepower} and \textit{SunContract} \cite{suncontract} utilize Ethereum smart contracts for green energy procurement and solar trading respectively. Both platforms are constrained by Ethereum's base-layer limitations, experiencing variable costs of \$1--50 per transaction depending on network congestion.

\subsection{Solana for DePIN Applications}

Solana's high-throughput, low-latency architecture has made it attractive for Decentralized Physical Infrastructure Networks (DePIN) \cite{depin}. Yakovenko's Proof-of-History (PoH) mechanism \cite{solana} enables theoretical throughput exceeding 65,000 TPS with sub-second finality. The Anchor framework \cite{anchor} further lowers the development barrier through type-safe abstractions and automated code generation. GridTokenX leverages these capabilities while extending them with domain-specific patterns for energy trading, including oracle-validated metering and dual-token economics.

\subsection{Smart Contract Security}

Smart contract security remains a critical concern. Atzei et al. \cite{atzei2017} cataloged common vulnerability patterns in Ethereum contracts, while Tsankov et al. \cite{securify} developed the Securify framework for automated verification. For Solana programs, Nelaturu et al. \cite{nelaturu2022} identified unique attack vectors including account confusion and missing signer checks. Our security analysis (Section~\ref{sec:security}) systematically addresses these vulnerabilities through Anchor's declarative constraint system and the STRIDE threat modeling framework \cite{stride}.

\subsection{Differentiating Contributions}

Table~\ref{tab:related-comparison} summarizes how GridTokenX differs from prior work. Our system uniquely combines Solana's performance with comprehensive energy-specific smart contract patterns, dual-token economics, and formal security analysis---aspects that are individually addressed but not holistically integrated in existing literature.

