\subsection{Dual-Tracker Protocol}

The architecture implements two parallel tracking systems that maintain cryptographic separation between physical energy flow and financial token flow:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Physical Tracker}: Registry (identity) + Oracle (meter readings) --- tracks real-world energy production and consumption through Ed25519-signed meter data.
    \item \textbf{Financial Tracker}: Energy Token (GRX minting) + Trading (order matching) --- manages tokenized energy value and market settlement.
\end{enumerate}

The systems are bridged through the \textit{token conservation invariant}, which ensures that token supply never exceeds verified physical energy production:

\begin{equation}
\Delta Supply_{GRX}(t) = \max\left(0,\; E_{net}(t) - E_{settled}(t)\right)
\label{eq:conservation}
\end{equation}

where $E_{net}(t) = E_{produced}(t) - E_{consumed}(t)$ represents cumulative net generation and $E_{settled}(t)$ represents the cumulative amount already converted to tokens. This invariant is enforced through a dual high-water mark mechanism in the Registry program, preventing both double-minting and double-claiming of energy credits.

\begin{definition}[Token Conservation]
For any meter $m$ at time $t$, the following invariants hold:
\begin{align}
settled\_net\_gen_m(t) &\leq net\_gen_m(t) \label{eq:hwm1} \\
claimed\_erc\_gen_m(t) &\leq settled\_net\_gen_m(t) \label{eq:hwm2}
\end{align}
where \eqref{eq:hwm1} prevents over-minting and \eqref{eq:hwm2} prevents double-claiming of ERC certificates.
\end{definition}

