\subsection{Common Design Patterns}

All programs follow consistent Anchor patterns, implementing a layered module structure with separate modules for error handling (\texttt{error\_code} macro), event definitions (\texttt{\#[event]} attribute), and state management (\texttt{\#[account]} structs). Each program declares a unique program ID, defines instruction handlers with declarative validation via the \texttt{\#[derive(Accounts)]} macro, and emits structured events for off-chain indexing. This consistency reduces cognitive load across the codebase and simplifies security auditing.

\subsection{PDA Derivation}

Program Derived Addresses (PDAs) provide deterministic, programmatically generated addresses that cannot be controlled by any external private key. The derivation uses a combination of static seed strings and dynamic account public keys, hashed together with the program ID to produce a unique address. A bump seed ensures the resulting address falls within the Ed25519 curve gap, guaranteeing it has no associated private key. This enables trustless authority--programs can sign for their own PDAs using the seeds and bump, eliminating the need for external key management in token minting and account creation.

\subsection{Account Validation}

Anchor's account validation system uses procedural macros to enforce security constraints at compile time. The \verb|#[account]| attribute supports declarative rules: \texttt{init} creates new accounts with specified space allocation, \texttt{payer} designates who funds the creation, and \texttt{seeds} with \texttt{bump} establish PDA derivation paths. Additional constraints like \texttt{has\_one} enforce account relationships, \texttt{constraint} enables custom boolean checks, and \texttt{address} validates against fixed public keys. This approach moves security checks from runtime logic to declarative annotations, reducing the attack surface by ensuring invariants are checked before instruction handlers execute.

Large accounts use \texttt{AccountLoader} for zero-copy deserialization, enabling efficient handling of large state without loading entire accounts into memory.

\section{Trading Program}
\label{sec:trading}

The Trading program implements the core marketplace with sharded order book architecture for horizontal scalability.

\subsection{Account Structures}

\subsubsection{Market Account}

The market account stores global trading parameters including authority, active orders, total volume, fee configuration, and price history supporting up to 256 shards.

\subsubsection{Order Account}

Orders track the full lifecycle from creation to settlement with fields for seller, buyer, amounts, pricing, order type, status, and shard assignment for scalability.

\subsection{Key Instructions}

\subsubsection{Create Sell Order}

Sell orders include optional ERC certificate validation. The implementation validates governance status, amount and price constraints, market price bounds, and optional ERC certificate validity before creating the order and emitting a SellOrderCreated event.

\subsubsection{Order Matching}

The match orders instruction performs atomic settlement by validating price compatibility (buy price $\geq$ sell price), checking available amounts, updating fill quantities, and emitting OrderMatched events upon successful matching. Algorithm~\ref{alg:matching} formalizes this process.

\begin{algorithm}[htbp]
\caption{Atomic Order Matching}
\label{alg:matching}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\REQUIRE Buy order $O_b$, Sell order $O_s$, Market $M$
\ENSURE Atomic settlement or rollback
\IF{$M.\text{is\_operational}() = \text{false}$}
    \RETURN \textsc{Error}(MaintenanceMode)
\ENDIF
\IF{$O_b.\text{price} < O_s.\text{price}$}
    \RETURN \textsc{Error}(PriceIncompatible)
\ENDIF
\STATE $Q_{match} \gets \min(O_b.\text{remaining}, O_s.\text{remaining})$
\STATE $P_{exec} \gets O_s.\text{price}$ \COMMENT{Price-time priority}
\STATE $V_{total} \gets Q_{match} \times P_{exec}$ \COMMENT{Checked arithmetic}
\STATE \textsc{TransferTokens}(Escrow $\rightarrow$ Buyer, $Q_{match}$)
\STATE \textsc{TransferPayment}(Buyer $\rightarrow$ Seller, $V_{total}$)
\STATE $fee \gets V_{total} \times M.\text{fee\_rate}$
\STATE $O_b.\text{filled} \gets O_b.\text{filled} + Q_{match}$
\STATE $O_s.\text{filled} \gets O_s.\text{filled} + Q_{match}$
\STATE \textsc{UpdateStatus}($O_b$, $O_s$)
\STATE \textsc{Emit}(OrderMatched\{$O_b$, $O_s$, $Q_{match}$, $P_{exec}$\})
\STATE $M.\text{total\_volume} \gets M.\text{total\_volume} + V_{total}$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\section{Energy Token Program}
\label{sec:energy-token}

The Energy Token program manages the GRX (GridTokenX) token, an SPL Token-2022 implementation with PDA-based minting authorities.

\subsection{Token Specifications}

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Name}: GridTokenX Energy Token
    \item \textbf{Symbol}: GRX
    \item \textbf{Decimals}: 9 (nano-GRX)
    \item \textbf{Standard}: SPL Token-2022
    \item \textbf{Mint Authority}: PDA with seed \texttt{token\_info\_2022}
    \item \textbf{Metadata}: Metaplex Token Metadata
\end{itemize}

\subsection{PDA-Based Minting}

The program uses Program Derived Address (PDA) as mint authority, enabling trustless minting without private key management. The PDA seeds use \texttt{token\_info\_2022} with the bump seed for signer derivation, allowing the program to sign CPI calls to the SPL Token program.

\subsection{Token Lifecycle}

The GRX token follows a well-defined state machine from minting through settlement, as illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:token-lifecycle}.

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\resizebox{\columnwidth}{!}{%
\begin{tikzpicture}[->, >=stealth, node distance=2.2cm, auto,
    state/.style={rectangle, draw, rounded corners, minimum width=1.8cm, minimum height=0.7cm, align=center, font=\small}]
    \node[state, fill=green!15] (mint) {Minted};
    \node[state, fill=blue!15, right=of mint] (held) {Held};
    \node[state, fill=orange!15, below=of held] (escrow) {Escrowed};
    \node[state, fill=purple!15, right=of held] (traded) {Traded};
    \node[state, fill=red!15, below=of traded] (burned) {Burned};
    
    \path (mint) edge node {\scriptsize airdrop/settle} (held)
          (held) edge node {\scriptsize create order} (escrow)
          (escrow) edge [bend left] node {\scriptsize cancel} (held)
          (escrow) edge node {\scriptsize match} (traded)
          (traded) edge node {\scriptsize redeem} (burned)
          (held) edge [bend left=45] node[above] {\scriptsize burn} (burned);
\end{tikzpicture}}%
\caption{GRX Token Lifecycle State Machine}
\label{fig:token-lifecycle}
\end{figure}

\subsubsection{Minting}

Tokens are minted based on validated energy production. The implementation verifies token authority, constructs CPI accounts for SPL Token-2022 minting using PDA signer seeds, updates total supply tracking, and emits a TokensMinted event.

\section{Oracle Program}
\label{sec:oracle}

The Oracle program serves as the trusted bridge between physical metering infrastructure and the blockchain, validating meter readings before they trigger token minting.

\subsection{Access Control}

Only the authorized API Gateway can submit readings. The implementation verifies the caller is the registered API gateway, checks oracle active status, and validates timestamps are not in the future.

\subsection{Anomaly Detection}

The Oracle implements multiple validation checks including range checks for energy values against maximum thresholds and production/consumption ratio validation for solar farm configurations.

\section{Registry Program}
\label{sec:registry}

The Registry program manages user identity, meter registration, and automatic token distribution for new participants.

\subsection{User Registration with Airdrop}

New users receive automatic GRX tokens upon registration (20 GRX airdrop with 9 decimals). The implementation initializes user account with authority, type, geolocation (lat/long, H3 index), status, and registration timestamp. After emitting UserRegistered event, it performs automatic airdrop via CPI to the Energy Token program if configured.

\subsection{Meter Management}

Meters are registered with fixed-size identifiers (32-byte arrays) for efficient zero-copy storage. The MeterAccount structure includes meter ID, owner, wallet address, meter type, zone ID, status, registration timestamp, last reading timestamp, and cumulative energy production/consumption totals.

\section{Governance Program}
\label{sec:governance}

The Governance program implements Proof-of-Authority (PoA) administration and Energy Renewable Certificate (ERC) lifecycle management.

\subsection{ERC Certificate Lifecycle}

ERC certificates track renewable energy attributes with fields for certificate ID, owner, energy amount, renewable source, status (Pending, Valid, Expired, Revoked), creation timestamp, expiration, trading validation flag, and validation metadata.

\subsection{Maintenance Mode}

The program supports emergency maintenance mode for system upgrades. The PoAConfig provides an is\_operational() method that checks maintenance mode status. Trading and other programs verify operational status before executing state-changing instructions.

\section{Cross-Program Invocation}
\label{sec:cpi}

The programs communicate through Anchor's CPI framework, enabling composable business logic across program boundaries. CPI enables one program to invoke instructions on another program within the same transaction, maintaining atomicity---if any CPI call fails, the entire transaction is rolled back.

\subsection{CPI Flows}

Four primary CPI patterns define inter-program communication:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Registry $\rightarrow$ Energy Token}: Automatic airdrop minting during user registration, where Registry invokes \texttt{mint\_tokens\_direct} with PDA signer seeds
    \item \textbf{Trading $\rightarrow$ Governance}: ERC certificate validation before order acceptance, ensuring only valid renewable certificates receive premium pricing
    \item \textbf{Oracle $\rightarrow$ Trading}: Market clearing triggers after valid readings, initiating batch settlement when sufficient liquidity exists
    \item \textbf{Energy Token $\rightarrow$ SPL Token}: Token interface operations for mint, burn, and transfer via the SPL Token-2022 program
\end{enumerate}

\section{Security Analysis}
\label{sec:security}

Security is paramount in a financial system handling real-value energy tokens. This section presents our threat model, attack vector analysis, and mitigation strategies.

\subsection{Threat Model}

We adopt the STRIDE framework \cite{stride} to systematically analyze threats across all system components. Table~\ref{tab:stride} presents the threat matrix.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{STRIDE Threat Analysis Matrix}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcccccc}
\toprule
\textbf{Component} & \textbf{S} & \textbf{T} & \textbf{R} & \textbf{I} & \textbf{D} & \textbf{E} \\
\midrule
User Authentication & $\bullet$ & $\circ$ & $\bullet$ & $\circ$ & $\circ$ & $\bullet$ \\
Smart Meter & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ & $\circ$ & $\circ$ & $\circ$ & $\circ$ \\
Smart Contracts & $\circ$ & $\bullet$ & $\circ$ & $\circ$ & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ \\
API Gateway & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ \\
Trading Engine & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ & $\circ$ & $\bullet$ & $\bullet$ \\
\bottomrule
\multicolumn{7}{l}{\small $\bullet$~= High risk \quad $\circ$~= Low/Medium risk} \\
\multicolumn{7}{l}{\small S=Spoofing, T=Tampering, R=Repudiation,} \\
\multicolumn{7}{l}{\small I=Info Disclosure, D=Denial of Service, E=Elevation} \\
\end{tabular}
\label{tab:stride}
\end{center}
\end{table}

\subsection{Attack Vectors and Mitigations}

We systematically address eight attack vectors with dedicated test coverage:

\subsubsection{Re-Entrancy Prevention}
Solana's single-threaded execution model and Anchor's account locking provide inherent re-entrancy protection. Additionally, all state updates follow the Checks-Effects-Interactions pattern: status fields are updated \textit{before} CPI calls to external programs, preventing state inconsistency if a callback occurs.

\subsubsection{Integer Overflow Protection}
All arithmetic operations use Rust's checked arithmetic methods (\texttt{checked\_add}, \texttt{checked\_mul}, \texttt{checked\_sub}, \texttt{checked\_div}), returning explicit errors instead of wrapping. Additionally, the platform uses saturating arithmetic for non-critical counters to prevent silent failures.

\subsubsection{Front-Running Resistance}
Solana's architecture provides natural front-running resistance: there is no public mempool, transactions are ordered by Proof-of-History timestamps, and the $\sim$400ms block time provides a narrow manipulation window. The order book enforces strict price-time priority, ensuring fair execution ordering.

\subsubsection{Double-Spending Prevention}
The escrow pattern locks tokens in a PDA-controlled account upon order creation. The dual high-water mark (Equations~\ref{eq:hwm1}--\ref{eq:hwm2}) prevents both double-minting of GRX tokens and double-claiming of ERC certificates.

\subsubsection{Authorization Enforcement}
Every instruction validates caller identity through Anchor's \texttt{has\_one} and \texttt{constraint} attributes. The Oracle program restricts meter submissions to the registered API Gateway address. Administrative functions require PoA authority verification through the Governance program.

\subsubsection{Replay Attack Prevention}
Each transaction includes a unique recent blockhash and monotonically increasing sequence numbers on meter readings, preventing replay of previously valid transactions.

\subsubsection{Economic Exploit Prevention}
Market bounds enforce minimum and maximum prices, preventing extreme value extraction. The PoA governance model enables emergency circuit breakers via maintenance mode when anomalous trading patterns are detected.

\subsubsection{Meter Data Integrity}
Smart meter readings require Ed25519 signatures verified by the Oracle program. Anomaly detection validates readings against configurable thresholds for maximum energy values and production/consumption ratios.

\subsection{Security Test Coverage}

Table~\ref{tab:security-tests} summarizes the 91 dedicated security tests.

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Security Test Coverage by Attack Vector}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
\textbf{Attack Vector} & \textbf{Tests} & \textbf{Status} \\
\midrule
Authorization bypass & 18 & Pass \\
