\section{Error Handling and Events}
\label{sec:errors-events}

\subsection{Custom Error Types}

Each program defines domain-specific errors using Anchor's \texttt{error\_code} macro. Error types include invalid amounts, prices outside market bounds, invalid or expired ERC certificates, trading validation failures, and maintenance mode restrictions.

\subsection{Event Emission}

All state changes emit structured events for off-chain indexing. Key events include SellOrderCreated (seller, order ID, amount, price, timestamp), OrderMatched (buy/sell order addresses, amount, price, timestamp), and TokensMinted (recipient, amount, timestamp).

\section{Deployment and Testing}
\label{sec:deployment}

\subsection{Anchor.toml Configuration}

Anchor.toml configuration specifies the toolchain version (0.32.0), program addresses for localnet deployment, provider settings (localnet cluster, wallet path), and test scripts. Program IDs are declared for Trading, Energy Token, Oracle, Registry, and Governance programs.

\subsection{Testing Framework}

Integration tests use Anchor's TypeScript testing utilities. Tests create program method calls with BigNumber parameters for order IDs, energy amounts, and prices, specify accounts including market, order, and authority public keys, submit RPC transactions, and verify resulting on-chain account state.

\section{Data Flow Architecture}
\label{sec:dataflow}

The GridTokenX platform implements a multi-layer data flow architecture that bridges physical energy infrastructure with blockchain state. The system follows a structured data flow decomposition (DFD) model across three levels.

\subsection{Level 0: Context Diagram}

At the highest level, the system interfaces with four external entities:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Prosumer (Seller)}: Registers devices, submits energy data, creates orders, receives payment
    \item \textbf{Consumer (Buyer)}: Registers, browses orders, executes trades, makes payments
    \item \textbf{Smart Meter System}: Provides signed energy readings with Ed25519 verification
    \item \textbf{Grid Operators}: Receives aggregated generation data for compliance reporting
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Level 1: Main Process Decomposition}

The system decomposes into seven core processes:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{User Management (1.0)}: Wallet validation, PDA creation, profile storage
    \item \textbf{Energy Recording (2.0)}: Meter reading verification, anomaly detection, surplus calculation
    \item \textbf{Token Minting (3.0)}: Settlement calculation, CPI to Energy Token, SPL minting
    \item \textbf{Order Management (4.0)}: Order validation, escrow locking, order book maintenance
    \item \textbf{Trade Settlement (5.0)}: Order matching, atomic settlement, payment transfer
    \item \textbf{ERC Management (6.0)}: Certificate issuance, validation, retirement tracking
    \item \textbf{Payment Processing (7.0)}: GRX transfer, event emission, trade recording
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Data Stores}

The architecture maintains seven primary data stores:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{D1: User Database} --- User profiles, wallet addresses, on-chain PDAs
    \item \textbf{D2: Meter Readings} --- Time-series energy production/consumption data
    \item \textbf{D3: Token Ledger} --- GRX token balances (SPL Token-2022 on-chain)
    \item \textbf{D4: Order Book} --- Active and historical trading orders
    \item \textbf{D5: Trade History} --- Completed trade records with settlement proofs
    \item \textbf{D6: ERC Registry} --- Energy Renewable Certificate lifecycle records
    \item \textbf{D7: Payment Records} --- Payment transaction audit trail
\end{itemize}

\section{Token Economics}
\label{sec:tokens}

\subsection{GRX Token Specification}

The GridTokenX Energy Token (GRX) is an SPL Token-2022 implementation with the following characteristics:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Name}: GridTokenX Energy Token
    \item \textbf{Symbol}: GRX
    \item \textbf{Decimals}: 9 (nano-GRX precision)
    \item \textbf{Supply Type}: Elastic (minted/burned based on verified energy)
    \item \textbf{Mint Authority}: PDA with seeds \texttt{[\"token\_info\_2022\"]}
    \item \textbf{Backing Ratio}: 1 GRX = 1 kWh of verified renewable energy
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Elastic Supply Mechanism}

Token supply dynamically adjusts based on oracle-validated meter readings. The supply at time $t$ is given by:

\begin{equation}
\text{Supply}(t) = \sum_{i=0}^{t} \text{Minted}_i - \sum_{i=0}^{t} \text{Burned}_i
\end{equation}

Minting is triggered when three conditions are simultaneously satisfied:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Net energy generation exceeds the previously settled amount: $E_{net}(t) > E_{settled}(t)$
    \item Oracle BFT consensus validates the meter reading with $3f+1$ backup oracles confirming authenticity
    \item Registry CPI invokes Energy Token mint instruction with PDA signer authority
\end{enumerate}

The minting quantity is precisely determined by:

\begin{equation}
Q_{mint} = \left\lfloor \left(E_{net}(t) - E_{settled}(t)\right) \times 10^9 \right\rfloor \text{ nano-GRX}
\label{eq:minting}
\end{equation}

where the floor function and $10^9$ scaling factor convert kWh to the token's 9-decimal precision, ensuring no fractional token creation.

\subsection{Value Components}

The GRX token derives value from three components:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Intrinsic Value}: Backed by BFT-validated meter data (1:1 kWh ratio)
    \item \textbf{Utility Value}: Required for platform trading (4 modalities supported)
    \item \textbf{Scarcity Value}: Supply strictly tied to verified production (no arbitrary minting)
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{GRX Token Lifecycle}

The GRX token supports multiple lifecycle operations beyond minting:

\textbf{Burning}: Token holders can burn GRX tokens to remove them from circulation permanently. This occurs when energy credits are redeemed or when users wish to exit positions. The burn instruction invokes SPL Token-2022's burn operation with PDA authority signing.

\textbf{Transfer}: Standard SPL token transfers enable peer-to-peer value exchange. The Energy Token program wraps SPL transfers with additional validation hooks for compliance tracking.

\textbf{Metadata}: Using Metaplex Token Metadata, each GRX token account stores extended metadata including mint authority, freeze authority, and custom attributes for regulatory reporting.

\subsection{Carbon Token (CRB)}

GridTokenX implements a dual-token model with Carbon Tokens (CRB) representing verified carbon offset credits:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Name}: GridTokenX Carbon Token
    \item \textbf{Symbol}: CRB
    \item \textbf{Decimals}: 9
    \item \textbf{Standard}: SPL Token-2022
    \item \textbf{Backing}: 1 CRB = 1 kg CO$_2$ equivalent offset
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Minting Sources}: CRB tokens are minted through three verified channels:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Solar energy generation (0.5 kg CO$_2$/kWh avoided)
    \item Wind energy production (0.4 kg CO$_2$/kWh avoided)
    \item Grid displacement verification via Oracle consensus
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Token Coupling}: GRX and CRB maintain a dynamic coupling ratio based on the grid carbon intensity factor. During high-carbon grid periods, CRB minting rates increase to incentivize renewable consumption:

\begin{equation}
\text{CRB}_{\text{mint}} = \text{GRX}_{\text{trade}} \times C_{\text{grid}} \times R_{\text{factor}}
\end{equation}
where $C_{\text{grid}}$ is the grid carbon intensity and $R_{\text{factor}}$ is the renewable displacement factor.

\subsection{Pricing Mechanisms}

GridTokenX implements multi-modal price discovery to accommodate diverse market conditions and user preferences:

\subsubsection{Order Book Pricing}

The primary trading mechanism uses a continuous order book with limit orders:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Bid-Ask Spread}: Market makers provide liquidity through competitive bid (buy) and ask (sell) prices
    \item \textbf{Price Matching}: Orders execute when bid price $\geq$ ask price, using VWAP (Volume-Weighted Average Price) for multi-order settlements
    \item \textbf{Market Bounds}: The Trading program enforces minimum and maximum price limits to prevent market manipulation
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{VWAP Settlement}

For batch clearing and complex multi-party trades, the system calculates:

\begin{equation}
P_{\text{VWAP}} = \frac{\sum_{i}(Q_i \times P_i)}{\sum_{i}Q_i}
\end{equation}

where $Q_i$ is the quantity and $P_i$ is the price of order $i$. This ensures fair price discovery even with asymmetric order sizes.

\subsubsection{Dynamic Pricing Factors}

Energy prices on the platform reflect multiple dynamic factors:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Grid Reference Price}: Tied to Thai Baht Chain (THBC) for fiat anchor
    \item \textbf{Time-of-Day}: Peak demand hours (18:00--22:00) command 15--25\% premiums
    \item \textbf{Weather Conditions}: Cloudy days increase solar scarcity pricing
    \item \textbf{ERC Premium}: Renewable energy certificates add 5--10\% green premium
    \item \textbf{Carbon Intensity}: High grid carbon periods increase CRB-coupled pricing
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{Price Oracle Integration}

The Oracle program provides reference pricing data:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{External Feeds}: Integration with grid utility tariffs and spot markets
    \item \textbf{On-Chain History}: 24-hour rolling price history stored in Market account
    \item \textbf{Consensus Validation}: Multiple oracle sources prevent price manipulation
\end{itemize}

