\section{Process Flows}
\label{sec:processes}

\subsection{Energy Production Recording}

The end-to-end energy data flow proceeds through six stages:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Generation}: Smart meter measures production/consumption in kWh
    \item \textbf{Signing}: Device signs reading with Ed25519 private key
    \item \textbf{Submission}: HTTPS POST to API Gateway with signature
    \item \textbf{Verification}: Gateway validates signature and meter registration
    \item \textbf{Storage}: Reading stored in PostgreSQL with \texttt{minted=false}
    \item \textbf{On-chain Update}: Meter PDA updated via Registry program
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Token Minting Process}

The automated minting workflow involves:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Polling service queries unminted readings every 60 seconds
    \item Registry calculates unsettled balance: $unsettled = net\_gen - settled\_net\_gen$
    \item Registry CPI to Energy Token program with settlement proof
    \item Energy Token mints GRX (1:1 with unsettled kWh) via SPL Token-2022
    \item Meter reading marked \texttt{minted=true} in database
    \item Token balance reflected in user's SPL token account
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Order Matching and Settlement}

The trading process follows atomic settlement principles:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Order Creation}: Prosumer creates sell order with ERC certificate (optional)
    \item \textbf{Escrow Locking}: GRX tokens locked in order escrow PDA
    \item \textbf{Matching}: Consumer initiates match with compatible buy order
    \item \textbf{Atomic Settlement}: Trading program executes all-or-nothing transfer
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Tokens: Escrow $\rightarrow$ Buyer
        \item Payment: Buyer $\rightarrow$ Seller
    \end{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Event Emission}: TradeExecuted event emitted for indexing
    \item \textbf{State Update}: Order status updated to FILLED
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Cross-Process Data Flows}

Five phases define the complete energy trading lifecycle:

\textbf{Phase 1: Energy Generation} --- Smart meter submits signed reading $\rightarrow$ API Gateway validates $\rightarrow$ Blockchain updates meter PDA

\textbf{Phase 2: Token Minting} --- Polling service detects unminted readings $\rightarrow$ Registry settles balance $\rightarrow$ Energy Token mints GRX

\textbf{Phase 3: Order Creation} --- Prosumer creates order $\rightarrow$ Tokens escrowed $\rightarrow$ Order visible in book

\textbf{Phase 4: Trade Execution} --- Consumer matches order $\rightarrow$ Atomic settlement $\rightarrow$ Payment transferred

\textbf{Phase 5: Event Synchronization} --- On-chain events $\rightarrow$ PostgreSQL records $\rightarrow$ WebSocket broadcast

\section{Research Methodology}
\label{sec:methodology}

This research adopts a pragmatic paradigm combining Design Science Research (DSR) \cite{hevner2004} and case study approaches to create an innovative, working blockchain platform for P2P energy trading.

\subsection{Research Questions}

\textbf{Primary Research Question (RQ):} How can blockchain technology enable efficient, transparent, and decentralized peer-to-peer energy trading while ensuring trust between prosumers and consumers?

\textbf{Secondary Research Questions:}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{RQ1 (Technical Feasibility):} What blockchain architecture and smart contract design patterns are required to implement a scalable P2P energy trading platform?
    \item \textbf{RQ2 (Token Economics):} How should energy tokenization be designed to maintain value stability and encourage market participation?
    \item \textbf{RQ3 (Market Mechanism):} What order matching mechanism provides efficient price discovery while ensuring fair access for all participants?
    \item \textbf{RQ4 (Governance):} How can decentralized governance enable community-driven platform evolution while maintaining operational stability?
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Design Science Research Framework}

Following Hevner et al. \cite{hevner2004}, this research creates four artifact types:

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{DSR Artifact Types}
\begin{center}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lp{5.8cm}@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Artifact} & \textbf{Description} \\
\midrule
Constructs & GRX Token, Prosumer, Settlement, ERC Certificate vocabulary \\
Models & P2P Trading, Token Economics, Governance Model \\
Methods & Order Matching, Settlement, Consensus \\
Instantiation & GridTokenX (six Anchor programs), TS SDK \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\label{tab:artifacts}
\end{center}
\end{table}

\subsection{Evaluation Criteria}

Technical evaluation metrics include:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Performance}: Transaction latency $<$ 5 seconds, throughput $>$ 100 TPS, finality $<$ 2 seconds
    \item \textbf{Security}: Zero critical vulnerabilities, test coverage $>$ 80\%
    \item \textbf{Scalability}: Linear scaling with participants, horizontal scaling capability
    \item \textbf{Economic}: Price stability (volatility $<$ 10\% daily), liquidity (bid-ask spread $<$ 1\%)
\end{itemize}

