\subsection{Discussion}

The performance advantage stems from three factors: (1) Solana's Proof-of-History consensus eliminates the communication overhead of traditional BFT protocols; (2) the sharded order book architecture enables horizontal scaling across up to 256 market shards; and (3) compute unit optimization (Section~\ref{sec:cu-optimization}) reduces per-transaction resource consumption by 45.5\%.

However, this comparison has important caveats. GridTokenX benchmarks were conducted on a private seven-node PoA cluster, while commercial platforms operate in production environments with heterogeneous network conditions. Power Ledger and Energy Web have demonstrated regulatory compliance and real user adoption that GridTokenX has not yet achieved. The throughput advantage is therefore a \textit{potential} rather than \textit{demonstrated} advantage at scale in production.

\section{Limitations and Future Work}
\label{sec:limitations}

\subsection{Current Limitations}

Despite the system's comprehensive architecture, several limitations warrant discussion:

\textbf{Centralized Oracle.} The current implementation relies on a single API Gateway as the oracle endpoint. While the architecture supports BFT consensus with 3f+1 backup oracles, the production deployment uses a centralized gateway, creating a single point of trust. Compromising this gateway would allow submission of falsified meter readings.

\textbf{Private Network Assumptions.} Performance benchmarks were conducted on a private seven-node PoA cluster with controlled network conditions. Public Solana mainnet deployment would introduce additional latency from validator geographic distribution, network congestion, and variable gas fees.

\textbf{Regulatory Compliance.} P2P energy trading faces significant regulatory barriers in most jurisdictions \cite{zhou2020}. The current system does not implement jurisdiction-specific compliance modules for energy regulation, tax reporting, or consumer protection requirements.

\textbf{Scalability Validation.} While the sharded order book supports 256 shards theoretically, testing was conducted with a single shard. Cross-shard coordination and its impact on matching latency remain unvalidated at scale.

\textbf{User Experience.} The system requires participants to manage Solana wallets and understand blockchain transaction mechanics, presenting an adoption barrier for non-technical prosumers.

\subsection{Future Work}

Several research directions extend this work:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Decentralized Oracle Network}: Implementing a multi-node BFT oracle with threshold signatures for meter reading validation, eliminating the single-point-of-trust limitation.
    \item \textbf{Zero-Knowledge Proofs}: Integrating ZK-SNARKs for privacy-preserving energy trading, where production volumes and trading positions remain confidential while settlement correctness is publicly verifiable.
    \item \textbf{Cross-Chain Bridge}: Enabling interoperability with Ethereum-based energy platforms via Wormhole bridge integration, extending the platform's reach to existing DeFi liquidity.
    \item \textbf{Machine Learning Pricing}: Deploying on-chain ML models for optimal price prediction based on weather forecasts, demand patterns, and grid carbon intensity.
    \item \textbf{Regulatory Sandbox}: Collaborating with Thai energy regulators (EGAT, ERC) to conduct regulatory sandbox testing for compliance validation.
    \item \textbf{Real-World Pilot}: Deploying GridTokenX in a Thai community microgrid with actual smart meters and prosumers to validate assumptions under real-world conditions.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This paper presented GridTokenX, a production-grade blockchain-based P2P energy trading platform implemented on Solana using the Anchor framework. The six-program architecture---Trading, Energy Token, Oracle, Registry, Governance, and Blockbench---provides clear separation of concerns while maintaining composability through Cross-Program Invocation.

Our empirical evaluation demonstrates that the system achieves sustained throughput of 4,200 TPS with 99.7\% success rate under load, representing a 42--280$\times$ improvement over existing blockchain energy platforms. The 45.5\% compute unit optimization reduces per-transaction costs to \$0.000007, making micro-transactions for energy trading economically viable. The dual-tracker protocol with high-water mark enforcement provides formal guarantees against double-spending, validated by 91 dedicated security tests.

Key technical contributions span five areas: (1) PDA-based authorities enabling trustless token minting without key management; (2) a dual high-water mark mechanism preventing double-minting and double-claiming; (3) sharded order book architecture supporting horizontal scaling; (4) comprehensive STRIDE-based security analysis covering eight attack vectors; and (5) standard Blockbench and TPC-C benchmark adaptation for blockchain energy trading evaluation.

While limitations remain---particularly the centralized oracle and lack of real-world pilot data---GridTokenX serves as a reference implementation for Anchor-based DePIN applications, demonstrating that high-performance blockchain infrastructure can meet the demanding requirements of real-time energy settlement. Future work will focus on decentralized oracle networks, zero-knowledge proofs for privacy-preserving trading, and regulatory sandbox collaboration with Thai energy authorities.

